liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ABC Sport journalist Samantha Lewis is right in the thick of it at Stadium Australia tonight, and says the woman of the hour has been Katrina Gorry. As predicted, the Matildas have struggled to find a point of attack thanks to the absence of captain Sam Kerr. Caitlin Foord has stepped into the centre-forward role, but she's barely had a touch of the ball in this opening half-hour. The real woman of the hour for Australia has been Katrina Gorry : not only has she been spraying line-breaking passes left and right, but she's been doing the dirty, ugly work off the ball like tackles, intercepts, and wrestling the ball back into her possession when the Matildas are under pressure. At one point, she was the last defender muscling off Republic of Ireland 's centre-forward, and at another point she was sprinting towards their goalkeeper, trying to close down a clearance. She's been absolutely everywhere, and will be the reason the team gets a result tonight — if they do!
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Analysis: Matildas struggle to find point of attack without Sam Kerr

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A beautiful ball from Mitch Starc, swinging to outside off, just clipping Duckett's outside edge and through to Carey! It's a big wicket, just ask Glenn McGrath on ABC radio. "Big wicket for the Australian's there!" McGrath says. "Today is about the Ashes, whoever wins today wins the Ashes." He goes for a single. England are 1-9.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: EDGED! TAKEN!

children.content: A beautiful ball from Mitch Starc, swinging to outside off, just clipping Duckett's outside edge and through to Carey!
(Getty Images)
It's a big wicket, just ask Glenn McGrath on ABC radio.
"Big wicket for the Australian's there!" McGrath says.
"Today is about the Ashes, whoever wins today wins the Ashes."
He goes for a single.
England are 1-9.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: "It took longer than England wanted but Australia are out," says Jim Maxwell on Test match special. So 17 bonus runs after the early overstep from Chris Woakes. Marnus Labuschagne said anything with a three in front of it would be a good total, and that might well be the case. Always hard to judge a pitch until both teams have batted. England are not going to hang around here - I'd expect Australia to be batting again later tonight one way or another - but this could be really exciting.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australia all out 317

children.content: "It took longer than England wanted but Australia are out," says Jim Maxwell on Test match special.
So 17 bonus runs after the early overstep from Chris Woakes.
Marnus Labuschagne said anything with a three in front of it would be a good total, and that might well be the case.
Always hard to judge a pitch until both teams have batted.
England are not going to hang around here - I'd expect Australia to be batting again later tonight one way or another - but this could be really exciting.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It was only a matter of time, Woakes looks back at the umpire but he's happy and Hazlewood was not hesitating, sprinting off the field to get ready to bowl. He goes for 4, Australia are all out.

children.content: Woakes takes 5-62, his first Ashes five-wicket haul

He goes for 4, Australia are all out.
